# Agency KPI Maturity Map

A comprehensive stage-by-stage matrix showing which KPIs to track, how to track them, what they mean, and what decisions they should inform at each level of agency maturity.

## How to Use This Map

This is a **reference matrix** for understanding:
1. Which KPIs matter most at your stage
2. How sophisticated your tracking should be
3. What decisions each KPI should inform
4. When to add complexity vs. keep it simple

**Navigation:**
- Each stage has its own section
- KPIs organized by category within each stage
- Includes tracking method, interpretation, and decision impact

---

## Rising Stage ($500K-$1.5M AGI)

### Stage Characteristics

**Leadership mode:** Practitioner-Manager (founder wearing all hats)
**Primary challenge:** Establish viable, repeatable business model
**Operational maturity:** Low—building foundation
**Planning horizon:** 30-60 days
**Team size:** 2-8 people
**Decision style:** Reactive, founder-centric

### Core KPI Priorities

**Track these (minimum viable dashboard):**
1. AGI (monthly)
2. Operating profit margin
3. Cash runway
4. Client retention (simple count)
5. Utilization (rough estimate)

**Don't worry about yet:**
- Detailed pipeline forecasts
- Cohort analysis
- NPS surveys
- Complex project profitability

---

### Financial Performance KPIs

| KPI | How to Track | What Success Looks Like | Key Decision Impact |
|-----|-------------|------------------------|---------------------|
| **AGI (Monthly)** | QuickBooks or simple spreadsheet | Consistent positive AGI 10+ months/year | Can we survive? Should we keep going? |
| **AGI%** | Calculate: AGI ÷ Total Revenue | 75-85% minimum | Are we too reliant on pass-through? |
| **Operating Profit Margin** | QuickBooks P&L | 10-25%, positive most months | Can founder pay themselves? |
| **Compensation %** | Payroll ÷ AGI | ≤50% (includes founder) | Can we afford this team? |
| **Cash Runway** | Bank balance ÷ monthly burn | 1-3 months (build to 3) | Do we have time to fix problems? |

**Tracking method:**
- Monthly P&L review (30 minutes)
- Simple spreadsheet tracking AGI, costs, margin
- Bank balance visible weekly

**Interpretation at this stage:**
- Positive = winning
- Trending up = progress
- Don't obsess over variance—focus on direction

**Common mistakes:**
- Over-analyzing small fluctuations
- Comparing to mature agency benchmarks
- Tracking too many metrics

---

### Forecasting & Pipeline KPIs

| KPI | How to Track | What Success Looks Like | Key Decision Impact |
|-----|-------------|------------------------|---------------------|
| **Current Client MRR** | Manual list of retainer clients | Stable or growing count | How much base revenue do we have? |
| **New Business Pipeline** | List in CRM or spreadsheet | 2-3 active opportunities always | Will we have work next month? |
| **Forecast Accuracy** | Don't track formally yet | N/A—just estimate next 30 days | Can we make payroll? |

**Tracking method:**
- Weekly: Update client list and pipeline
- Monthly: Review what closed vs. what was projected
- No formal variance analysis

**Interpretation at this stage:**
- "Will there be work next month?" is the only question
- High variance acceptable
- Focus on keeping pipeline from going empty

**What NOT to do:**
- Complex weighted forecasts
- Formal variance reviews
- Quarterly planning cycles

---

### Client Retention & Account Health

| KPI | How to Track | What Success Looks Like | Key Decision Impact |
|-----|-------------|------------------------|---------------------|
| **Client Retention (Count)** | Simple headcount monthly | Losing <2 clients per year | Are clients generally satisfied? |
| **Churn Rate** | Optional—not critical yet | ≤15-20% annually acceptable | Do we have fundamental delivery issues? |
| **Client Results** | Informal—founder knows | Clients get tangible wins | Are we delivering value? |

**Tracking method:**
- Count clients at end of each month
- Note who churned and why (informal)
- No formal NPS or surveys yet

**Interpretation at this stage:**
- Every lost client feels significant (small base)
- Learn from each loss informally
- Don't need sophisticated tracking

**What to watch for:**
- Churn >25% annually = major delivery issue
- Pattern in why clients leave = systemic problem
- Client complaining = immediate attention

---

### Sales & Marketing Efficiency

| KPI | How to Track | What Success Looks Like | Key Decision Impact |
|-----|-------------|------------------------|---------------------|
| **New Clients Won** | Simple count | 1-2 per month | Are we growing? |
| **Win Rate** | Rough estimate | >25-30% | Is sales working at all? |
| **CAC** | Optional—hard to calculate cleanly | Establish baseline | How much does growth cost? |

**Tracking method:**
- Count proposals sent and won
- Estimate marketing/sales costs monthly
- Don't stress precision

**Interpretation at this stage:**
- Focus on momentum, not efficiency
- Any predictable new business = success
- Don't optimize prematurely

**What NOT to worry about:**
- LTV:CAC ratios
- Payback period calculations
- Channel-specific ROI

---

### Productivity & Capacity

| KPI | How to Track | What Success Looks Like | Key Decision Impact |
|-----|-------------|------------------------|---------------------|
| **Utilization** | Rough estimate—hours worked | 60-75% average | Are we overwhelmed or underworked? |
| **AGI per FTE** | AGI ÷ team size | $140K-160K | Can we afford our team? |
| **Overtime** | Feel vs. formal tracking | Occasional, not constant | Is team burning out? |

**Tracking method:**
- Weekly team check-ins
- General sense of workload
- No formal time tracking yet

**Interpretation at this stage:**
- Team feels sustainable = good
- Constant firefighting = capacity issue
- Idle time = growth needed

**What to watch for:**
- Utilization >90% sustained = hire soon
- Utilization <50% sustained = revenue problem
- Team complaining of overwork = take seriously

